=== Relationship with Trading Desks

*How Strategists Support Traders:*
- *Macro Views*: Providing top-down perspective to inform trader positioning
- *Catalysts*: Identifying upcoming events and market-moving data
- *Themes*: Highlighting cross-asset opportunities (e.g., "divergence trade")
- *Risk Scenarios*: Stress-testing portfolios against macro shocks
- *Client Flow*: Explaining client positioning and flow trends
- *Market Color*: Interpreting market moves and news developments

*How Traders Use Strategy Research:*
- Directional positioning (e.g., short AUD based on strategist bearish call)
- Hedging decisions (e.g., buying downside protection based on risk scenarios)
- Client conversations (sharing strategy views to generate flow)
- Risk management (adjusting exposures based on macro outlook)
- Idea generation (identifying relative value opportunities from strategist analysis)

*Tension Points:*
- Strategists have medium-term view (3-6 months), traders often shorter-term (days-weeks)
- Strategists make calls in research, traders must execute and manage risk
- When strategy calls wrong, traders may lose money - can create friction
- Traders focused on P&L, strategists on research quality and client relationships

*Best Practices for Collaboration:*
- Regular communication (daily morning calls, ad-hoc discussions)
- Clear time horizons (strategist specifies "3-month view" vs "tactical")
- Transparency about conviction and risk (strategist communicates uncertainty)
- Two-way feedback (traders share market intelligence, strategists incorporate)

=== MiFID II Impact on Strategy Research

*Background:*
MiFID II (Markets in Financial Instruments Directive II), effective January 2018 in Europe, unbundled research from execution services. While Australian firms aren't directly subject to MiFID II, many have global clients affected by it.

*Implications for Strategists:*
- Increased pressure to demonstrate tangible value from research
- More formalized client feedback and research consumption tracking
- Some firms charge explicitly for strategy research (vs bundled with execution)
- Greater focus on actionable recommendations and measurable performance
- Enhanced documentation of client usage and research impact

*Response Strategies:*
- Track record maintenance (documenting performance of calls)
- Client surveys (measuring satisfaction and research usage)
- Customization (tailored research for specific client needs)
- Multi-channel delivery (written, video, in-person to maximize engagement)
- Integration with trading (clear links between research and execution)

